The commissioner may issue a written order suspending or revoking the designation of an agent if the commissioner finds that:
The agent violates this subtitle or a rule adopted or an order issued under this subtitle;
The agent does not cooperate with an examination, investigation, or subpoena issued by the commissioner;
The agent has engaged in fraud, intentional misrepresentation, or gross negligence;
The agent has been convicted of a felony;
The agent has been convicted of a misdemeanor related to the business of money transmission;
The agent has been convicted of a misdemeanor involving theft, fraud, or breach of trust;
The competence, experience, character, or general fitness of the agent or a person in control of the agent indicates that it is not in the public interest to permit the agent to be engaged in the business of money transmission;
The agent is engaged in or is engaging in an unsafe or unsound practice;
The agent is engaged in, or is engaging in, an unfair and deceptive act or practice as that act or practice relates to the business of money transmission;
The agent is insolvent;
The agent has applied for an adjudication of bankruptcy, reorganization, arrangement, or other relief under the United States Bankruptcy Code, 11 U.S.C. secs. 101 to 110; or
The agent fails to timely remit all money legally due to its licensee as required by this subtitle; or
The agent, any executive officer, or other person in control of the agent is listed or become listed on the specially designated nationals and blocked persons list prepared by the United States Department of the Treasury or United States Department of State under Presidential Executive Order No. 13224 as a potential threat to commit terrorist acts or to finance terrorist acts.
